 in it, irrespective of how many negative expressions are used. The central aim of this book is to describe Strict Negative Concord in some Slavic and Finno-Ugric languages. In particular, the volume gives an insight into the forms Strict Negative Concord manifests itself in Russian, Polish, Czech, Slovenian (Slavic), Finnish, Hungarian, Mari (Finno-Ugric) and the closely related Selkup (Samoyedic) to a wide linguistic community. It aims to create a platform for comparison with similar phenomena in well-described European languages.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aFinno-Ugric. 4aSlavische Sprachen. 4aSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aStrict Negative Concord, Licensing, Locality Conditions.1 aBradley, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCegłowski, Piotr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCegłowski, Piotr, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDalmi, Gréte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalmi, Gréte, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDotlačil, Jakub, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDočekal, Mojmír, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDäbritz, Chris Lasse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregorčič, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirvonen, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIlc, Gašper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenardič, Jakob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuda, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular